Striking bill approved

Last Thursday, Congress and the president finally met on
middle ground by approving the presidential line-item veto.
This is truly a landmark event, since the Republican-controlled
Congress and the Democrat White House have had little to
agree on since they came into office. Just how far apart they
usually are can be seen by how long it took to pass the line-
item veto; it was one of President Clinton’s campaign promis-
es and a part of the Republican Contract with America. Both
parties wanted the bill, but it took almost two years for
Congress to relinquish some of its lawmaking power to the
president. But as of July 1 of this year, Congress will do just
that.

Thousands of bills are introduced into Congress every year.
You might remember from the elementary school cartoon
“How a Bill Becomes a Law” that each bill has to be
approved, voted on, amended, approved again, et cetera. Every
time a bill is amended, it usually gets one or two riders
attached to it to make it more agreeable to everyone. Even if a
congressman doesn’t like a specific bill, he or she can attach a
rider clause to it to make the whole thing more palatable.
Sometimes this kind of congressional artistry can lead to a bill
which has one little clause tacked on to it which will cause the
entire bill to be vetoed by the president.

Especially in the past two years, this kind of thing has run
rampant. President Clinton exercised his veto power more
times than most people can count, in many instances because
of a rider clause. For example, the recent welfare-reform bill
that made it to Clinton’s desk was never passed, even though
the president said he liked a majority of the bill. He vetoed the
whole bill because he thought the Medicaid cuts were too
drastic, so the whole bill was lost. Though they have seen

A many of their pet projects (like welfare reform) vetoed by the

president, the members of the Republican Congress still saw
the value of the line-item veto.

Opponents of the line-item veto argue that it is unconstitu-
tional, since the president will have the ability to sign laws
that were not technically approved by Congress. The president
will be able to strike out the clauses he does not like but still
sign the other parts of the bill into law. In a literal sense, the
opponents of the bill are correct; the president does not have to
sign the bill as it is when he receives it. However, the parts of
a bill left after the line-item veto is exercised will have been
approved by Congress. The line-item veto does not allow the
president to write his own clauses, only to strike out existing
ones. Even once the veto is exercised, Congress can still over-
ride it, like any other veto, with a two-thirds majority vote.

Hopefully, the line-item veto will allow important legislation
to become law, without the frequently outlandish and some-
times irrelevant riders blocking their passage.

