During presidential elections,
candidates with little chance of
winning typically take wild
stances on the issues in an effort
to win support from important
voting blocs. This sort of des-
peration is evident from the dis-
turbingly protectionist rhetoric
being espoused by candidate
Pat Buchanan in an effort to win
votes from voters disaffected by
economic change.

Buchanan has seized upon
President Clinton’s bailout of
the Mexican economy last year
as a campaign issue in an effort
to bolster his flagging cam-
paign. To hammer home his
“America First” it-heme,
Buchanan constantly repeats
this statement to voters every-
where at every opportunity:
“Why did we send [Mexico]
$50 billion? Because the bonds
were coming due, my friends!
So we got the New York
bankers — Citibank, Chase
Manhattan and Goldman, Sachs
— off the hook. But guess
who's on the hook? You and
your grandchildren!”

Is Buchanan’s statement true?
Did the United States “send”
Mexico $50 billion in cash?
Certainly not. Of the 50 billion
Buchanan was referring to, 12
billion comes from Japan,
Europe, Latin America and
Canada. Another 18 billion
comes from the International
Monetary Fund.

In _reality, we actually have
“sent” Mexico about 20 billion,
far less than the 50 billion
Buchanan talks about. In his
speeches, Buchanan implies
that President Clinton sat down
and wrote a check for 50 billion
to the Mexican government
without any strings attached,
which is very wrong. The
United States is lending this
money with interest. In the long
run, the Mexico loans won’t
cost the American people a
dime.

Also, Buchanan neglected to
mention that the Mexican gov-
emment has recently repaid the
first installment of the loan

Michael
Berquist

ahead of schedule. In the event
that the Mexican government
cannot repay the loans, it must
put up its highly valuable oil
reserves as collateral. This has
led Buchanan’s Mexican coun-
terparts to moan about the “sur-
rendering” of Mexican sover-
eignty to the United States.
Buchanan callously responds to
the charges of being a protec-
tionist by retorting, “I plead
guilty to trying to protect the
American worker.”

Rather than reject Buchanan’s
isolationist rhetoric, his fellow
Republicans have done their
best to court Buchanan voters
by embracing the fundamental
ideas behind his rhetoric, even
while they decry his protection-
ism. Recently, Senator and
Republican presidential nomi-
nee Bob Dole, once a consistent
free trade advocate until he
began to kowtow to right-wing
voters, rejected the idea of
adding Chile to the NAFTA
agreement, explaining that
America is “choking” on free
trade agreements.

Some people have argued that
America is still an international-
ist nation committed to protect-
ing freedom abroad, citing such
examples as a recent poll that
says two-thirds of the American
people want the U.S. to play an
“active role” in foreign affairs.
Unfortunately, while the public
might echo this ideal in spirit, it
is unwilling tomake sacrifices
necessary to achieve this goal.

Another recent poll says that
a majority of Americans feel
that we should withdraw from
the NAFTA agreement, despite
no evidence that it has caused
any harm to the United States
(alarmingly enough, two-fifths
of Republican voters have
called Buchanan’s solutions the
“right ones” for America).
Sixty-five percent of the
American public feels that we
should tax imported goods in an
effort to protect the jobs and

wages of American workers.
Stanford economist Paul
Krugman debunked this sort of
thinking by pointing out that
barriers to trade typically boost
prices within the very markets
they seek to protect, give con-
sumers fewer choices and
weaken the world economy.

The historical precedent
against protectionism is persua-
sive: In 1929 the United States
imported about $6 billion of
products. Thanks to the Smoot-
Hawley tariff, which was
intended to shield America’s
economy from the weaknesses
exposed by the stock market
crash of 1929, imports fell to
just $2 billion three years later
in 1932. In retaliation, European
markets increased tariffs, slow-
ing American exporting from
$7 billion to $2.4 billion during
the same time period.
Unsurprisingly, unemployment
skyrocketed from 3.3 percent in
1929 to a stunning 25 percent.
America’s GDP was sliced in
half. As both sides raised tariffs
back and forth, the world econ-
omy collapsed.

Today, too many American
jobs depend upon free trade. An
estimated 770,000 American
jobs depend upon export to
Mexico alone. One in six jobs
in the United States depend
upon exports. To seal our bor-
ders as Buchanan and his naive
supporters advocate would be
crazy. It would do little more
than wreck our own economy
and stagnate the economies of
countries that trade with us. The
ripple effect would succeed in
doing just what Buchanan is
trying to prevent: destroying
America’s fragile economy,
much like the Smoot-Hawley
tariff did over 60 years ago.
Buchanan and his supporters
ought to think their decisions
through carefully before they
make the decision which may
feel good to make but which
may also have repercussions.

Michael J. Berquist is a calmn-
nistfor The Pitt News.

